<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-503-597  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 503 597.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Oct 8 1990 v7 n41 p15(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Worldspan set to merge travel nets onto backbone. (WorldspanTravel Agency Information Services)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Desmond, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Worldspan Travel Agency Information Services announces the mergerof its two airline reservation networks onto a backbone supportiveof links to LANs at travel agencies.andP;  The company is consideringfilling the backbone with either the X.25 or the IBM systemsarchitecture protocol to enable it to have advanced distributedapplications.andP;  A source at Worldspan notes that the company hasplans for a net that will be supportive of 30 million messages aday by 1993, and will allow for growth for at least 10 years.andP;  Thecompany has yet to chose a vendor that will figure out the networkconfiguration and provide equipment.andP;  The company is likely tochose a systems integrator capable of supplying or procuring allof the net components and providing global support.andP;  Worldspan isjointly owned by Delta and Northwest Airlines.andP;  The merger alsobrought about a combination of the two companies' networks, DataII and PARS.andP;  The new Worldspan network will provide a switch fromthe Airline Link Control (ALC) protocol employed by both PARS andData II to Synchronous Data Link Control or the X.25.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Worldspan Travel Agencies Information Service (communicationsystems).andO;Topic:     Network Access ProceduresReservation SystemsLocal Area NetworksTravel IndustryInformation Resources Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>